IT is easier to agree than disagree. But we can learn a lot from conversations where we don’t see eye to eye — if we can listen and talk rationally, that is. Unfortunately, many of us either shy away completely from disagreements or lose it when things do not go our way. These five tips can help keep disagreements constructive — whether you are talking to a parent, friend or anyone else: Respect goes beyond difficult conversations, of course. Being helpful and considerate toward family members, teachers, or coaches in our everyday actions helps all of us (again, parents included!) establish a foundation for those times when we might disagree
